00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:05.450
So I went to India to
learn meditation in 1970.

00:02:05.450 --> 00:02:09.034
I'd taken an Asian
philosophy course

00:02:09.034 --> 00:02:11.070
in the university
I was going to,

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:13.910
and the university
also had a program,

00:02:13.910 --> 00:02:15.490
like an independent
study program.

00:02:15.490 --> 00:02:17.870
And if you created a
project that they liked,

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:19.740
you could go anywhere
in the world.

00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:25.870
And I had this kind
of strange desire

00:02:25.870 --> 00:02:26.940
to learn how to meditate.

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:28.000
So I created a project.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.083
I said, I want to go to
India and learn mediation.

00:02:30.083 --> 00:02:32.890
And they said OK, so off I went.

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:39.540
I came back in 1974 with the
encouragement and, actually,

00:02:39.540 --> 00:02:41.790
insistence of one of
my teachers to teach.

00:02:41.790 --> 00:02:43.100
So I came back as a teacher.

00:02:43.100 --> 00:02:47.470
So that was really the
beginning of many things.

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:51.330
And in those days, one never
heard the word mindfulness.

00:02:51.330 --> 00:02:53.920
And if you said you
were-- as I would

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:55.767
in some social
situation-- people

00:02:55.767 --> 00:02:56.850
would say, what do you do?

00:02:56.850 --> 00:02:58.100
And I'd say, teach meditation.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:02.850
It would be kind of
like, ew, that's weird.

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:04.910
Which is very,
very different now.

00:03:04.910 --> 00:03:11.160
So there are lots of ways
of slicing and dicing

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:13.710
and categorizing
meditation practice.

00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:17.270
I always think of meditation
is a skills training,

00:03:17.270 --> 00:03:20.950
and primarily in three
different qualities.

00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:23.280
One is concentration,
so that we're

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:26.220
less scattered or
distracted-- less fragmented.

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:29.160
We feel more of a sense
of presence and wholeness

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:31.780
and focus.

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.080
One is mindfulness
itself, which feels

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:37.110
like the word of the hour.

00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:39.340
Classically, it means
a quality of attention

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:42.510
so that as we pay
attention, our perception's

00:03:42.510 --> 00:03:45.320
not so distorted by bias.

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:51.570
We're not laying on so many
preconceptions or old fears

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:55.730
or assumptions, and
we can get much closer

00:03:55.730 --> 00:03:59.680
to our experience in that
way, without so many veils

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:01.030
intruding.

00:04:01.030 --> 00:04:04.380
And therefore, mindfulness
is considered the basis

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:07.420
for insight or wisdom, because
we can get so much more

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:10.430
connected to things as they
actually are when we're not,

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:13.240
for example, taking the present
moment's experience of it's

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:16.517
difficult and projecting it into
a seemingly unchanging future,

00:04:16.517 --> 00:04:19.100
like, what's this terrible thing
going to feel like in a week?

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:21.060
It's going to be
worse, you know?

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:22.630
And so on.

00:04:22.630 --> 00:04:25.690
So that's really the
skill of mindfulness.

00:04:25.690 --> 00:04:28.370
And then compassion
and loving kindness

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:30.550
is like the third great
skill of meditation,

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:33.060
and it is considered a
skill, which is often

00:04:33.060 --> 00:04:35.710
in the West considered
kind of peculiar.

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:40.320
It's a little bit kind of cold
or mechanistic in some ways,

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:43.290
we think, like the idea
of training and compassion

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:46.080
is just offputting.

00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:48.010
And I don't know if
it's that we tend

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:49.391
to think of
compassion as a gift,

00:04:49.391 --> 00:04:52.015
and you've either got it or you
don't, and if you don't, you're

00:04:52.015 --> 00:04:52.900
out of luck.

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:56.375
Or it's like a seemingly
spontaneous emotional response,

00:04:56.375 --> 00:04:58.450
and there's nothing you can do.

00:04:58.450 --> 00:05:05.260
But another way of looking
at it from the point of view

00:05:05.260 --> 00:05:07.540
of meditation is
that compassion is

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:10.890
like an emergent property
of how we pay attention.

00:05:10.890 --> 00:05:13.890
And if we shift the way we pay
attention-- so, for example,

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:16.900
we're not overlooking someone
or looking through them

00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:18.570
or discounting
them, we're actually

00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:22.660
looking at them-- then because
of that different quality

00:05:22.660 --> 00:05:25.740
of attention, there will be a
different sense of connection,

00:05:25.740 --> 00:05:27.000
and therefore, compassion.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.600
So it, too, is a kind
of attention training.

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:34.270
So in terms of the
larger ways of practice,

00:05:34.270 --> 00:05:37.470
there's some practices
that really are largely

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:42.180
about cultivating mindfulness,
where our goal is not

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:44.180
to have a particular
experience at all,

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:48.650
but to change our relationship
to whatever experience comes up

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:50.655
so we're more present,
we're more aware,

00:05:50.655 --> 00:05:55.280
we're more balanced, and there's
more insight that can develop.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:59.389
And that's the first practice
that we're going to do.

00:05:59.389 --> 00:06:01.430
Many of you, I'm sure,
are very familiar with it.

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:02.820
A very classic
practice where you

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:09.200
start with awareness of the
breath, which is certainly

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:11.920
not the only way to
lay a foundation,

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:13.470
but it's such a
common way in part

00:06:13.470 --> 00:06:17.054
because as my early teachers
would say, first of all,

00:06:17.054 --> 00:06:18.470
you don't have to
believe anything

00:06:18.470 --> 00:06:21.610
in order to feel your breath.

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:25.670
It's not tied to any kind
of dogma or faith tradition

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:26.980
or lack of faith tradition.

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:29.400
If you're breathing,
you can be meditating.

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:32.130
And then as one teacher said-- I
always found it very charming--

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:34.530
he said the breath
is very portable.

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:37.230
So, you know, we come together.

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:41.590
It's like a formal,
determined sitting.

00:06:41.590 --> 00:06:45.020
OK, now I'm going to come
together and sit with people.

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:47.120
And we get used to
coming back to the moment

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:49.490
and coming back
to ourselves using

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:50.660
the vehicle of the breath.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:53.450
And then you're
at work, or you're

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:56.330
in traffic, or whatever it is.

00:06:56.330 --> 00:06:58.810
You have that
means of returning.

00:07:01.770 --> 00:07:03.710
And the other set
of practices, which

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:09.470
we'll do next, while they
involve, to a certain degree,

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:11.860
the development of
mindfulness and a greater

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:15.690
clarity about our
experience, I call them

00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:17.870
sort of like the stretch.

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:21.070
And that is the
sense of realizing

00:07:21.070 --> 00:07:26.080
that our attention can be highly
habituated in certain ways,

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:28.640
and we're just going
to see what it's like.

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:29.760
It's like an experiment.

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:31.670
We're going to see
what it's like when

00:07:31.670 --> 00:07:36.430
we step outside the confines
of that ordinary way of paying

00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:38.230
attention.

00:07:38.230 --> 00:07:42.990
And that's that whole group of
concentration practices based

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:47.510
on compassion and love
and kindness and so on.

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:49.770
They're not meant to be
pretentious and weird and

00:07:49.770 --> 00:07:51.920
phony, which is
often the feeling.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:53.140
Like, ew.

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:55.130
That's a little offputting.

00:07:55.130 --> 00:07:59.390
But in truth, I think
they're pretty radical,

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:03.960
because it's like taking
some risks with our awareness

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:06.260
in ways we don't necessarily do.

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:09.190
So, for example, if you
think about that person

00:08:09.190 --> 00:08:11.220
you normally look right
through, because they

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:14.890
don't count in some way,
what happens when you look

00:08:14.890 --> 00:08:17.105
at them instead of through them?

00:08:17.105 --> 00:08:19.480
Or if you're the kind of person
who at the end of the day

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:21.430
is looking back at
yourself through the day,

00:08:21.430 --> 00:08:24.670
and you pretty well only
remember the mistakes you made,

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:27.030
and the things you didn't
do really perfectly,

00:08:27.030 --> 00:08:30.520
and what you could have done
better, let's just say--

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:33.049
AUDIENCE: I have no idea
what you're talking about.

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:34.940
SHARON SALZBERG:
No one ever does.

00:08:34.940 --> 00:08:37.210
And then the stretch
is not to pretend, oh,

00:08:37.210 --> 00:08:40.159
I had a perfect day and did
everything magnificently,

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:42.549
but not to be limited
by that, right?

00:08:42.549 --> 00:08:45.660
To include also, wow, I
have that to be grateful,

00:08:45.660 --> 00:08:48.615
or I did that well, or
there was that goodness

00:08:48.615 --> 00:08:51.270
in what came my way, right?

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:55.040
So both sets of practices--
the mindfulness practices

00:08:55.040 --> 00:08:58.520
that help bring us closer to our
experience and those practices

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:00.580
which are like experimenting
with awareness--

00:09:00.580 --> 00:09:02.880
are based on inclusion.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:06.190
We include experiences
in a field of awareness.

00:09:06.190 --> 00:09:10.251
We include more and more beings
in a field of connection.

00:09:10.251 --> 00:09:10.750
OK?

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:14.330
So rather than my saying
more, we'll practice some,

00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:17.090
and then we'll get
into some discussion.

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:22.690
So all right.

00:09:22.690 --> 00:09:25.410
Don't look at that
clock, whatever you do.

00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:28.434
AUDIENCE: The clock is a test.

00:09:28.434 --> 00:09:29.850
SHARON SALZBERG:
So to begin with,

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:34.010
we're going to do a
sitting based primarily

00:09:34.010 --> 00:09:35.305
on mindfulness practice.

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:40.570
And interestingly
enough, the core value

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:43.570
of this kind of practice
is said to be balance.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:46.270
Unlike other pursuits
we might engage in

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:47.810
or other endeavors
we might have,

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:51.195
where we get into a
kind of acquisitive,

00:09:51.195 --> 00:09:53.810
almost grabby kind
of mode-- like, well,

00:09:53.810 --> 00:09:57.690
if I have a great sitting,
I can leave at the break.

00:09:57.690 --> 00:10:02.440
Instead, the work is to bring
our system into greater balance

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:04.390
with the belief that
out of that balance

00:10:04.390 --> 00:10:10.170
will come the insight and the
growth and awareness and so on,

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:12.755
so that some of that balance
is experienced right away

00:10:12.755 --> 00:10:13.490
in our posture.

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:16.060
You want some
energy in your body.

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:18.470
You want to see if your
back can be straight.

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:20.240
But like so much energy.

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:23.400
You're really hypervigilant
and you're so uptight.

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:25.500
You also want to be
relaxed, but not, like,

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:28.880
so relaxed that you're
way slumped over

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:30.620
as though you
couldn't care less.

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:33.510
So see if you can feel
your way into what

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:34.985
feels like a balanced posture.

00:10:40.430 --> 00:10:41.940
And you can close
your eyes or not.

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:43.550
However you feel most at ease.

00:10:43.550 --> 00:10:47.380
If your eyes are open, they
can also be a little bit open.

00:10:47.380 --> 00:10:49.460
You can find a spot
to rest your gaze.

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:51.610
Let it go.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:54.480
And if you get really
sleepy, as sometimes happens

00:10:54.480 --> 00:10:57.070
with your eyes closed, you
can also just open your eyes

00:10:57.070 --> 00:10:57.980
and continue on.

00:11:16.430 --> 00:11:20.610
Very often, we start
by listening to sound.

00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:23.460
It's a way of
relaxing deep inside,

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:26.799
allowing our experience
to come and go.

00:11:26.799 --> 00:11:28.340
And of course, we
like certain sounds

00:11:28.340 --> 00:11:29.960
and we don't like others.

00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:33.830
But we don't have to chase after
them to hold on or push away.

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:35.330
Just let them come, let them go.

00:11:51.330 --> 00:11:53.560
It's like the sounds
wash through you.

00:12:16.249 --> 00:12:18.790
And bring your attention to the
feeling of your body sitting.

00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:20.240
Whatever sensations
you discover.

00:12:56.050 --> 00:12:58.690
Bring your attention
to your hands.

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:02.080
See if you can make the shift
from the more conceptual level,

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:06.210
like of fingers, to the
world of direct sensation,

00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:10.305
picking up pulsing, throbbing,
pressure, whatever it might be.

00:13:10.305 --> 00:13:13.167
You don't have to name
those things, but feel them.

00:13:38.550 --> 00:13:41.930
Now bring your attention to
the feeling of your breath.

00:13:41.930 --> 00:13:45.910
In this system, it's just
the normal, natural breath,

00:13:45.910 --> 00:13:47.515
wherever you feel
it most distinctly.

00:13:47.515 --> 00:13:51.740
You don't have to try to make
the breath deeper or different.

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:54.050
See if there's a place where
it's strongest for you--

00:13:54.050 --> 00:13:58.400
maybe at the nostrils or
the chest or the abdomen.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:01.730
If you find that place, you
can bring your attention

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:02.780
there and just rest.

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:07.740
See if you can feel one breath.

00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:15.980
Without concern
for what's already

00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:19.230
gone by, without leaning forward
for even the very next breath.

00:14:19.230 --> 00:14:19.900
Just this one.

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:34.070
If you like, you can use
a very quiet mental note,

00:14:34.070 --> 00:14:38.884
like in, out, or rising,
falling to help support

00:14:38.884 --> 00:14:40.050
the awareness of the breath.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:40.940
But very quiet.

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:45.060
So your attention
is really going

00:14:45.060 --> 00:14:47.370
to feeling the breath
one breath at a time.

00:15:22.160 --> 00:15:27.100
And if sounds or images,
sensations or emotions

00:15:27.100 --> 00:15:31.690
should arise, but they're
not all that strong,

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:34.010
if you can stay connected to
the feeling of the breath,

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:35.390
just let them flow on by.

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:36.430
You're breathing.

00:15:36.430 --> 00:15:37.852
It's just one breath.

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:46.282
But if something
is really strong,

00:15:46.282 --> 00:15:51.610
and you get lost in thought,
spun out in a fantasy,

00:15:51.610 --> 00:15:56.760
or you fall asleep,
you get really

00:15:56.760 --> 00:15:59.400
disconnected from the
breath, don't worry about it.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:04.930
We say the most important
moment in the whole practice

00:16:04.930 --> 00:16:07.380
is the moment after
you've been gone,

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:09.800
after you've been distracted.

00:16:09.800 --> 00:16:13.830
That's the moment where the
training actually takes place.

00:16:13.830 --> 00:16:16.200
We practice letting go gently.

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:17.780
We practice beginning again.

00:16:21.770 --> 00:16:24.390
Maybe you have to do it
again 10 seconds later.

00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:25.195
Doesn't matter.

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:29.100
We let go.

00:16:29.100 --> 00:16:30.590
We begin again.

00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:32.070
Just shepherd your
attention back

00:16:32.070 --> 00:16:36.140
to the feeling of the breath.

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:38.470
And if you have to do
that a few billion times

00:16:38.470 --> 00:16:40.600
in the next few
minutes, it's OK.

00:21:08.416 --> 00:21:09.790
Isn't that amazing
that no matter

00:21:09.790 --> 00:21:13.560
what happens, we can
always begin again?

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:18.430
Maybe you went far far, far
away for a good long time.

00:21:18.430 --> 00:21:19.080
It's OK.

00:21:22.181 --> 00:21:24.030
It's what one of
my teachers called

00:21:24.030 --> 00:21:26.080
exercising the
letting go muscle.

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:29.000
We practice letting go,
and with a full heart,

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:32.580
not feeling diminished or
that we failed, we start over.

00:22:22.777 --> 00:22:26.256
[CHIMING]

00:22:41.720 --> 00:22:43.220
SHARON SALZBERG:
That's my new bell.

00:22:43.220 --> 00:22:45.331
I had to use it.

00:22:45.331 --> 00:22:46.080
It's so beautiful.

00:22:49.940 --> 00:22:53.490
OK, do you have any questions
about anything you experienced,

00:22:53.490 --> 00:22:59.680
or anything I said,
or any comments?

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:02.230
And then we'll go on.

00:23:02.230 --> 00:23:03.050
Yeah?

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:03.966
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:07.410 --> 00:23:12.330
I was wondering if you could
talk to us a little more

00:23:12.330 --> 00:23:13.806
about Di Pama and [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:24.710 --> 00:23:27.450
SHARON SALZBERG: OK,
so the question was,

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:31.280
since I had used the phrase
my teacher or my teachers,

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:36.040
especially I had one teacher--
this woman named Di Pama, who

00:23:36.040 --> 00:23:38.950
was not famous, and she
was not a celebrity.

00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:41.980
Somebody wrote a book about her.

00:23:41.980 --> 00:23:46.660
The second version of it, I
think, is called "Di Pama."

00:23:46.660 --> 00:23:49.410
And it was very interesting,
because unlike some teachers,

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:53.420
she was most remarkable,
really, for her presence.

00:23:53.420 --> 00:23:55.670
And so it was a little hard
to write a book about her,

00:23:55.670 --> 00:23:59.320
because you didn't have the
illuminating sentence that

00:23:59.320 --> 00:24:02.160
changed your whole life or
something that you really

00:24:02.160 --> 00:24:04.030
wanted to be able to share.

00:24:04.030 --> 00:24:05.230
But it was just, like, wow.

00:24:05.230 --> 00:24:07.900
She was the most loving
person I ever met.

00:24:07.900 --> 00:24:09.650
Di Pama was one of
my early teachers.

00:24:09.650 --> 00:24:10.780
Di Pama is a nickname.

00:24:10.780 --> 00:24:14.150
It means deep is mother.

00:24:14.150 --> 00:24:17.140
And she was the person,
actually, who told me to teach.

00:24:17.140 --> 00:24:19.625
She's the reason that
I became a teacher.

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:30.410
She was most impressive to me,
really, because of her story.

00:24:30.410 --> 00:24:33.040
She was a woman who'd been
through tremendous suffering

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:34.210
in her own personal life.

00:24:34.210 --> 00:24:38.400
She'd been put into an
arranged marriage when

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:42.010
she was 12 years old,
and she and her husband

00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:43.890
actually fell deeply in love.

00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:46.880
And then they didn't have
children for about 18 years.

00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:49.570
And then they had
three children.

00:24:49.570 --> 00:24:51.630
Two of her children died.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:55.430
And then one day, her
husband died really suddenly.

00:24:55.430 --> 00:24:59.370
He just wasn't feeling well,
and he died by that evening.

00:24:59.370 --> 00:25:02.230
And she still has one
daughter, Dipa, to raise.

00:25:02.230 --> 00:25:03.860
But she was completely
grief stricken.

00:25:03.860 --> 00:25:05.060
She just went to bed.

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:06.857
She couldn't get out of bed.

00:25:06.857 --> 00:25:08.940
And they were living in
Burma, because her husband

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:10.190
had been in the civil service.

00:25:10.190 --> 00:25:18.100
And the doctor came to see
her, and he said to her,

00:25:18.100 --> 00:25:20.550
you're actually going
to die of a broken heart

00:25:20.550 --> 00:25:22.350
unless you do something
about your mind.

00:25:22.350 --> 00:25:24.700
You should learn
how to meditate.

00:25:24.700 --> 00:25:27.835
And she got up out of bed and
she went to the retreat center,

00:25:27.835 --> 00:25:30.570
and she learned how to meditate.

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.690
And when she emerged,
it's like she'd

00:25:33.690 --> 00:25:36.260
taken all of that suffering
and all of that pain

00:25:36.260 --> 00:25:38.690
and she'd turned it
into enormous compassion

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:39.430
for everybody.

00:25:39.430 --> 00:25:43.820
And she was just the most
loving, amazing person,

00:25:43.820 --> 00:25:48.550
because she knew for all of us,
our lives can change on a dime,

00:25:48.550 --> 00:25:52.090
and there was no one left
out of her sense of love

00:25:52.090 --> 00:25:58.254
and connection, in a very
ordinary kind of way, you know?

00:25:58.254 --> 00:26:02.300
Like, oh, did you
have enough tea?

00:26:02.300 --> 00:26:05.040
Would you like some more tea?

00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:08.500
And the lack of
self-preoccupation

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:10.580
was so remarkable, because
I'd often look at her

00:26:10.580 --> 00:26:12.580
and think, well, if I'd
been through what you've

00:26:12.580 --> 00:26:15.670
been through, would I care
about someone else's tea?

00:26:15.670 --> 00:26:17.120
Maybe not, you know?

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:20.100
But she'd used all that
in a beautiful way.

00:26:20.100 --> 00:26:23.380
So when she told me
to teach, it was 1974,

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:25.500
and I went to say goodbye
to her in Calcutta.

00:26:25.500 --> 00:26:27.680
I was coming back for
what I was absolutely

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:31.260
convinced was a very brief
return to the United States

00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:33.710
before I went back to India
to live the rest of my life

00:26:33.710 --> 00:26:36.130
there being a student.

00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:40.270
And she said, when you go back
to America, you'll be teaching.

00:26:40.270 --> 00:26:41.245
And I said, no I won't.

00:26:41.245 --> 00:26:42.370
And she said, yes you will.

00:26:42.370 --> 00:26:43.825
And I said, no I won't.

00:26:43.825 --> 00:26:44.950
And she said, yes you will.

00:26:44.950 --> 00:26:47.280
And I said no I won't.

00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:49.790
And then she said two things
that were really extraordinary.

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:52.130
One was, she said, you
really understand suffering.

00:26:52.130 --> 00:26:54.930
That's why you should teach.

00:26:54.930 --> 00:26:57.210
And I had never thought
of like the personal pain

00:26:57.210 --> 00:26:59.790
I had gone through as having
been a credential for anything,

00:26:59.790 --> 00:27:02.282
really, you know?

00:27:02.282 --> 00:27:03.615
You really understand suffering.

00:27:03.615 --> 00:27:04.630
That's why you should teach.

00:27:04.630 --> 00:27:07.030
And then she said, you can
do anything you want to do.

00:27:07.030 --> 00:27:08.750
It's just you're
thinking you can't do it

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:10.450
that's going to stop you.

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:14.092
And I left her room
thinking, no I won't.

00:27:14.092 --> 00:27:19.199
And I came back to the US
and began teaching and more

00:27:19.199 --> 00:27:21.490
invitations would come and
more invitations would come,

00:27:21.490 --> 00:27:24.610
and one day we established
this retreat center

00:27:24.610 --> 00:27:25.750
in Massachusetts.

00:27:25.750 --> 00:27:30.540
And somewhere after
that, I thought, oh, I

00:27:30.540 --> 00:27:33.250
guess I'm not going back
there to live after all.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:34.640
I guess I live here now.

00:27:49.840 --> 00:27:50.655
Anybody else?

00:27:56.110 --> 00:28:00.580
Maybe I'll use her, which is a
wonderful feeling, thank you,

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:04.295
as the introduction for the
loving kindness meditation.

00:28:08.230 --> 00:28:12.780
Because I think also,
in this society,

00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:14.907
we can think of kindness
and loving-- loving

00:28:14.907 --> 00:28:16.240
kindness is a weird word anyway.

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:17.450
We don't necessarily use it.

00:28:17.450 --> 00:28:23.230
But even compassion,
as weakness.

00:28:23.230 --> 00:28:28.350
I mean, someone told me
if you google compassion,

00:28:28.350 --> 00:28:31.120
very quickly,
fatigue will come up.

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:32.000
Compassion fatigue.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.809
We think of kindness often
as a secondary virtue.

00:28:34.809 --> 00:28:36.350
It's like, if you
can't be brilliant,

00:28:36.350 --> 00:28:39.445
and you can't be courageous,
and you can't be wonderful,

00:28:39.445 --> 00:28:40.741
eh, be kind.

00:28:40.741 --> 00:28:41.240
You know?

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:42.450
It's nice.

00:28:42.450 --> 00:28:45.280
It's not great, but
it's good, you know?

00:28:45.280 --> 00:28:48.700
It's good enough, kind of.

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:51.540
But I think of somebody like
Di Pama, and it's great.

00:28:51.540 --> 00:28:54.050
It's a great, great
thing to encounter

00:28:54.050 --> 00:28:58.380
that kind of caring energy
from somebody, where you really

00:28:58.380 --> 00:29:01.300
feel they're not in
it for themselves.

00:29:01.300 --> 00:29:06.850
They're just wanting to help or
be there or be present, or just

00:29:06.850 --> 00:29:12.970
energetically, that
field is so amazing.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:15.869
And I don't think of her
with a kind of scorn,

00:29:15.869 --> 00:29:18.160
like, eh, you couldn't do
anything else with your life,

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:20.380
so you became loving, you know?

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:25.110
It's like, it's a very different
quality of appreciation

00:29:25.110 --> 00:29:28.720
that I think we actually
do have when we think maybe

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:31.720
about people we've
encountered or so on.

00:29:31.720 --> 00:29:37.520
So one of the problems
with mindfulness practice

00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:41.440
is the word, and the words
that get associated with it,

00:29:41.440 --> 00:29:43.570
like accept things
the way they are.

00:29:43.570 --> 00:29:45.440
You going to be
with your experience

00:29:45.440 --> 00:29:48.835
without judgement that can sound
so passive and so complacent,

00:29:48.835 --> 00:29:52.320
like you're just going to
sit there no matter what.

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:55.340
And so it takes a
real exploration

00:29:55.340 --> 00:29:58.960
to understand it's a
dynamic, vital relationship.

00:29:58.960 --> 00:30:00.460
Like, once I was
teaching somewhere,

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:03.560
and I started the
instructions in the same way.

00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:05.270
Like, sit and listen to sound.

00:30:05.270 --> 00:30:07.345
And somebody immediately
raised their hand

00:30:07.345 --> 00:30:09.720
and said, well, what if it's
the sound of the smoke alarm

00:30:09.720 --> 00:30:10.219
I hear?

00:30:10.219 --> 00:30:12.870
Should I sit here and be mindful
of the sound of the smoke

00:30:12.870 --> 00:30:14.570
alarm, or should I get up?

00:30:14.570 --> 00:30:17.210
And I said, I'd get up.

00:30:17.210 --> 00:30:19.980
But just hearing the words, I
want to accept things the way

00:30:19.980 --> 00:30:23.610
they are, can sound a little
dull, you know, like that.

00:30:23.610 --> 00:30:25.930
And of course, there
are tremendous problems

00:30:25.930 --> 00:30:29.445
with words like loving kindness,
and kindness, and compassion.

00:30:29.445 --> 00:30:33.530
And I think it demands that
same kind of exploration

00:30:33.530 --> 00:30:37.920
and experimentation to get a
deeper sense of what's meant.

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:40.890
I think of loving kindness
as an acknowledgement--

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:44.780
a very deep acknowledgement--
of the connection that exists.

00:30:44.780 --> 00:30:46.422
It doesn't mean that
you like somebody.

00:30:46.422 --> 00:30:48.380
It doesn't mean you're
going to take them home.

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:50.088
It doesn't mean you're
going to give them

00:30:50.088 --> 00:30:54.040
all your money, or any money.

00:30:54.040 --> 00:30:57.210
It means this almost like
bone deep acknowledgement

00:30:57.210 --> 00:31:00.510
that our lives have something
to do with one another.

00:31:00.510 --> 00:31:04.860
And so many things bring
us to that understanding.

00:31:04.860 --> 00:31:08.610
Certainly, environmental
consciousness brings us there.

00:31:08.610 --> 00:31:10.610
Even epidemiology
brings us there.

00:31:10.610 --> 00:31:11.870
Economics brings us there.

00:31:11.870 --> 00:31:14.645
What happens over there
doesn't nicely stay over there.

00:31:14.645 --> 00:31:16.050
It ripples out over here.

00:31:16.050 --> 00:31:18.550
And what we do, it
matters, because

00:31:18.550 --> 00:31:20.485
of those waves of connection.

00:31:20.485 --> 00:31:22.130
It's just the nature of things.

00:31:22.130 --> 00:31:27.500
And so it's not always
pleasant, but it's true

00:31:27.500 --> 00:31:30.100
that our lives have something
to do with one another.

00:31:30.100 --> 00:31:34.620
And the lead lived of that,
the heart's response to that,

00:31:34.620 --> 00:31:36.990
is what we mean by
loving kindness.

00:31:36.990 --> 00:31:41.330
It doesn't mean you're forcing a
certain feeling or emotion that

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:43.050
isn't really there at all.

00:31:43.050 --> 00:31:51.370
It's more that sensibility, that
real, real sense that everybody

00:31:51.370 --> 00:31:52.600
counts.

00:31:52.600 --> 00:31:53.455
Everybody matters.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.430
Maybe my favorite expression
of loving kindness

00:31:58.430 --> 00:32:00.640
came when I was teaching
in Washington, DC.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:04.610
It was in this rented space
which was an elementary school.

00:32:04.610 --> 00:32:06.250
And they had the
rules of kindness

00:32:06.250 --> 00:32:09.520
on these sheets of
paper along the wall.

00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:12.044
And my favorite, favorite
rule of kindness-- it

00:32:12.044 --> 00:32:13.960
was things like respect
everyone on the inside

00:32:13.960 --> 00:32:14.870
and on the outside.

00:32:14.870 --> 00:32:17.730
But my favorite
rule of all of them

00:32:17.730 --> 00:32:20.100
was, everybody gets to play.

00:32:20.100 --> 00:32:21.780
Everybody gets to play.

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:25.640
Everybody is not my best friend,
but everybody gets to play.

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:28.340
So that's very much the
sense of loving kindness.

00:32:28.340 --> 00:32:30.040
And we practice in
the way I described--

00:32:30.040 --> 00:32:33.900
not forcing a feeling or trying
to pretend you feel something

00:32:33.900 --> 00:32:36.335
you don't, but kind of
stretching our awareness

00:32:36.335 --> 00:32:39.730
to pay attention to the
people we usually ignore,

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:42.620
to consider the good
within ourselves instead

00:32:42.620 --> 00:32:44.340
of only the mistakes we've made.

00:32:44.340 --> 00:32:47.760
We kind of play with our
awareness in various ways

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:53.790
to see what might then
follow in the nature of care

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:56.330
and compassion.

00:32:56.330 --> 00:32:58.746
So in this practice, instead
of centering our attention

00:32:58.746 --> 00:33:00.120
around the feeling
of the breath,

00:33:00.120 --> 00:33:02.610
we center our attention
around the silent repetition

00:33:02.610 --> 00:33:04.960
of certain phrases.

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:07.290
The phrases may not be
the most predominant thing

00:33:07.290 --> 00:33:08.200
in any given moment.

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:09.450
That's fine.

00:33:09.450 --> 00:33:12.440
You may have a very
strong sense of the being

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:15.770
you're offering
loving kindness to.

00:33:15.770 --> 00:33:19.480
You may have an emotion,
or not, coming up.

00:33:19.480 --> 00:33:21.290
But the phrases are
like the bottom line.

00:33:21.290 --> 00:33:23.055
It's what we can
keep returning to,

00:33:23.055 --> 00:33:26.140
to have a place to
rest our attention.

00:33:26.140 --> 00:33:29.909
And the phrases are the
conduit for our attention.

00:33:29.909 --> 00:33:32.200
It's the way we're paying
attention in a different way.

00:33:35.770 --> 00:33:37.960
The phrases are words,
and therefore they're

00:33:37.960 --> 00:33:40.410
going to be imperfect,
so I usually suggest

00:33:40.410 --> 00:33:44.860
to people, choose good
enough phrases so they're not

00:33:44.860 --> 00:33:45.625
bothering you.

00:33:48.009 --> 00:33:49.800
Even if they don't seem
absolutely perfect,

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:53.410
the idea is to choose phrases
that are kind of general so

00:33:53.410 --> 00:33:56.700
that you're not constantly
thinking, like, what about you?

00:33:56.700 --> 00:33:57.780
Maybe happy?

00:33:57.780 --> 00:33:59.080
Well, I don't know about you.

00:33:59.080 --> 00:34:01.050
Like, you get really
lazy when you're happy.

00:34:01.050 --> 00:34:02.550
Maybe content.

00:34:02.550 --> 00:34:04.030
No, content's even worse.

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:07.860
It's just like, because
the power of the practice

00:34:07.860 --> 00:34:10.380
is going to be from
the gathering of all

00:34:10.380 --> 00:34:12.650
of our attention behind
one phrase at a time.

00:34:12.650 --> 00:34:14.840
We want to keep
things simple, right?

00:34:14.840 --> 00:34:18.030
Again, it's like
letting go and returning

00:34:18.030 --> 00:34:21.360
is the movement of the practice.

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:25.520
And that's how it develops,
through paying attention

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:27.255
in different ways.

00:34:27.255 --> 00:34:31.260
The construct-- the grammatical
construct of the phrases--

00:34:31.260 --> 00:34:34.170
is usually may I and may you.

00:34:34.170 --> 00:34:37.414
May I be happy, may I be
peaceful, may you be happy,

00:34:37.414 --> 00:34:39.000
may you be peaceful.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:40.310
Some people don't like that.

00:34:40.310 --> 00:34:44.139
It sounds too much like
pleading or imploring.

00:34:44.139 --> 00:34:47.360
One of my friends
told me-- she told me

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:50.236
it was the hortatory
subjunctive part of speech,

00:34:50.236 --> 00:34:52.610
and she said it's like, you
hand someone a birthday card,

00:34:52.610 --> 00:34:54.401
and you say, may you
have a happy birthday.

00:34:54.401 --> 00:34:56.099
May you have a great new year.

00:34:56.099 --> 00:34:56.765
It's a blessing.

00:34:56.765 --> 00:34:58.330
It's a giving.

00:34:58.330 --> 00:35:00.380
It's actually a
generosity practice.

00:35:00.380 --> 00:35:01.306
It's gift giving.

00:35:01.306 --> 00:35:04.110
We're giving ourselves
that quality of energy.

00:35:04.110 --> 00:35:06.830
We're giving someone else
that quality of energy.

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:10.090
OK, so the basic bookends
of doing the practice

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:14.230
are starting with
yourself, and ending

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:16.890
with the extension of loving
kindness to all beings

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:17.990
everywhere to all of life.

00:35:17.990 --> 00:35:19.990
And what you do in the
middle might be different

00:35:19.990 --> 00:35:21.372
all the time.

00:35:21.372 --> 00:35:23.080
Maybe you have a friend
who's in trouble,

00:35:23.080 --> 00:35:24.300
so you want to include them.

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:26.020
Or someone you feel
very grateful to,

00:35:26.020 --> 00:35:27.550
and you want to include them.

00:35:27.550 --> 00:35:28.550
Or whatever it might be.

00:35:28.550 --> 00:35:30.770
So I'll guide you through
just one variation

00:35:30.770 --> 00:35:34.860
of the many possibilities
of doing it.

00:35:34.860 --> 00:35:36.830
So again, if you
sit comfortably,

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:38.375
and you can close
your eyes or not.

00:35:47.170 --> 00:35:50.296
Let your energy
settle into your body.

00:35:58.540 --> 00:36:01.130
See if there are three
or four phrases that

00:36:01.130 --> 00:36:04.660
work for you as that
sense of gift giving

00:36:04.660 --> 00:36:07.990
for yourself, and
ultimately for others.

00:36:07.990 --> 00:36:11.770
Common phrases are things
like may I be happy,

00:36:11.770 --> 00:36:12.965
may I be peaceful.

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:28.100
May I live with ease, which
means in the things of day

00:36:28.100 --> 00:36:31.040
to day life, like
livelihood and family,

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:32.805
may it not be a struggle.

00:36:32.805 --> 00:36:34.880
May I live with ease.

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:36.270
May I be happy.

00:36:36.270 --> 00:36:40.008
May I be peaceful.

00:36:40.008 --> 00:36:41.820
May I live with
ease, or whatever

00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:42.985
phrases you want to use.

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:48.620
And just gently repeat
them over and over again

00:36:48.620 --> 00:36:50.660
with enough space
and enough silence

00:36:50.660 --> 00:36:52.870
so that it's a rhythm
that's pleasing to you.

00:37:07.690 --> 00:37:09.990
All kinds of feelings
may come and go, or none.

00:37:09.990 --> 00:37:11.560
It doesn't matter.

00:37:11.560 --> 00:37:15.330
The power of the practice is
in that complete wholehearted

00:37:15.330 --> 00:37:17.510
presence behind one
phrase at a time.

00:38:24.010 --> 00:38:26.620
Now think of somebody who is
like an embodiment of loving

00:38:26.620 --> 00:38:29.400
kindness and compassion.

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:30.380
Maybe you've met them.

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:31.410
Maybe you haven't.

00:38:31.410 --> 00:38:34.180
Maybe they exist
now or historically

00:38:34.180 --> 00:38:35.100
or even mythically.

00:38:40.300 --> 00:38:45.601
And imagine that being offering
loving kindness to you.

00:38:45.601 --> 00:38:48.310
Now put yourself in the
position of the recipient.

00:38:54.540 --> 00:38:56.340
And again, all kinds
of feelings may come.

00:38:56.340 --> 00:38:57.770
You may feel embarrassed.

00:38:57.770 --> 00:39:00.330
You might feel entitled.

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:02.830
All kinds of things.

00:39:02.830 --> 00:39:05.630
But let them wash through you
as you steady your attention

00:39:05.630 --> 00:39:07.020
on the repetition
of the phrases.

00:40:02.530 --> 00:40:04.530
Maybe it's that
being or someone else

00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:07.060
comes to mind who's been
like a mentor for you,

00:40:07.060 --> 00:40:09.130
a benefactor for you.

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:11.780
They've helped pick you up
when you've fallen down,

00:40:11.780 --> 00:40:14.566
or maybe they've
inspired you from afar.

00:40:14.566 --> 00:40:16.790
And if someone like
that comes to mind,

00:40:16.790 --> 00:40:18.860
you can bring them here.

00:40:18.860 --> 00:40:19.895
Get an image of them.

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:24.210
Say their name to yourself.

00:40:24.210 --> 00:40:26.150
Get a feeling for their
presence and offer

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:28.800
the phrases of loving
kindness to them.

00:40:28.800 --> 00:40:31.890
Give them that same gift.

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:33.780
Again, even if the
words are imperfect,

00:40:33.780 --> 00:40:37.885
it's OK, because they're the
conduit for the heart's energy.

00:43:08.710 --> 00:43:09.700
And then a friend.

00:43:09.700 --> 00:43:12.100
The first friend
who comes to mind.

00:43:12.100 --> 00:43:14.650
Bring them here.

00:43:14.650 --> 00:43:16.190
Again, you can get
an image of them,

00:43:16.190 --> 00:43:18.800
or say their name to yourself.

00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:20.870
Get a feeling for their
presence and offer

00:43:20.870 --> 00:43:23.436
the phrases of loving
kindness to them.

00:45:15.540 --> 00:45:17.930
And then everybody here,
including yourself.

00:45:28.930 --> 00:45:31.140
May we be happy.

00:45:31.140 --> 00:45:33.250
May we be peaceful.

00:45:33.250 --> 00:45:36.150
May we live with ease.

00:45:36.150 --> 00:45:38.106
Or whatever phrases
you may be using.

00:46:27.760 --> 00:46:30.080
And then all beings everywhere.

00:46:30.080 --> 00:46:32.000
All people, all
creatures, all those

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:38.955
in existence near and
far, known and unknown.

00:46:38.955 --> 00:46:47.032
May all beings be happy, be
peaceful, live with ease.

00:47:54.624 --> 00:47:55.620
SHARON SALZBERG: OK.

00:47:55.620 --> 00:47:56.590
MALE SPEAKER: Awesome.

00:47:56.590 --> 00:47:57.798
SHARON SALZBERG: [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:57.798 --> 00:47:58.830
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:47:58.830 --> 00:48:00.530
Thank you so much.

00:48:00.530 --> 00:48:05.370
Does anybody have any questions
about how the practice went,

00:48:05.370 --> 00:48:09.067
and then we'll just pass
this around as needed?

00:48:09.067 --> 00:48:09.900
SHARON SALZBERG: OK.

00:48:12.589 --> 00:48:13.630
AUDIENCE: So [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:17.081 --> 00:48:20.039
I get the basic
idea, but I always

00:48:20.039 --> 00:48:23.983
had this nagging question which
is that-- especially if you're

00:48:23.983 --> 00:48:26.761
talking about creatures
instead of just humans, well,

00:48:26.761 --> 00:48:29.010
some creatures are going to
be eating other creatures.

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:29.310
SHARON SALZBERG: I know.

00:48:29.310 --> 00:48:30.685
AUDIENCE: And so
they're not both

00:48:30.685 --> 00:48:32.270
going to be happy
at the same time.

00:48:32.270 --> 00:48:35.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:35.590 --> 00:48:37.840
SHARON SALZBERG: I need to
repeat the question, right?

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:43.280
Yes, so the question was kind
of a discomfort at the offering

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:44.710
of loving kindness
to all beings,

00:48:44.710 --> 00:48:47.809
because it's basically
illogical, that especially

00:48:47.809 --> 00:48:49.350
when you're offering
loving kindness,

00:48:49.350 --> 00:48:52.580
say, to all creatures, since
creatures eat other creatures,

00:48:52.580 --> 00:48:55.080
they're not all going to
be happy at the same time.

00:48:55.080 --> 00:48:57.560
That is totally true.

00:48:57.560 --> 00:49:00.465
Sometimes I think of loving
kindness practice as landing us

00:49:00.465 --> 00:49:01.840
right in the center
of a paradox.

00:49:05.070 --> 00:49:09.370
And sometimes I think of
it as it's meant, really,

00:49:09.370 --> 00:49:15.600
to the arena of transformation
of loving kindness practice is

00:49:15.600 --> 00:49:17.390
our field of intention.

00:49:17.390 --> 00:49:20.030
It's how we are relating
in terms of inclusion

00:49:20.030 --> 00:49:25.280
and exclusion, in terms
of noticing or ignoring,

00:49:25.280 --> 00:49:28.740
in terms of opening
or shutting off.

00:49:28.740 --> 00:49:32.940
So that's the transformation,
and so that's our test.

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:36.400
It's not easy, and it's
not going to happen.

00:49:36.400 --> 00:49:39.570
But nonetheless, our
own commitment in life

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:41.440
is to include
rather than exclude,

00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:45.610
and to recognize the
suffering of beings.

00:49:45.610 --> 00:49:47.450
That is a part of nature.

00:49:47.450 --> 00:49:48.980
It's a part of life.

00:49:48.980 --> 00:49:53.130
And to ourselves, not
be causing more harm,

00:49:53.130 --> 00:49:57.370
to the best of our
ability, and so on.

00:49:57.370 --> 00:50:02.130
And also, it brings us to what's
a really exquisite balance

00:50:02.130 --> 00:50:06.010
that's often talked about
between, say, loving kindness

00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:08.900
and compassion on the
one side, and just

00:50:08.900 --> 00:50:10.570
equanimity on the other.

00:50:10.570 --> 00:50:13.690
It's like, yeah, this
is the way things are.

00:50:13.690 --> 00:50:17.490
And there's a kind
of poignancy in that.

00:50:17.490 --> 00:50:24.520
in that I often
say and feel it's

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:27.470
too bad it's not my
universe to control,

00:50:27.470 --> 00:50:31.320
because it might be
better if it were,

00:50:31.320 --> 00:50:33.570
or at least I think it would be.

00:50:33.570 --> 00:50:35.470
But it's not.

00:50:35.470 --> 00:50:38.290
Whether it's an immediate
situation-- one on one

00:50:38.290 --> 00:50:44.214
with a friend or colleague,
or it's kind of more

00:50:44.214 --> 00:50:47.116
a global look at the
nature of things.

00:50:49.640 --> 00:50:53.690
We want beings to be happy,
and we can't make it so.

00:50:53.690 --> 00:50:55.770
And yet we need to
do what we can do.

00:50:55.770 --> 00:50:58.410
That's not a call for passivity.

00:50:58.410 --> 00:51:02.330
But what we do needs to
be done in that context

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:03.820
of understanding, you know?

00:51:03.820 --> 00:51:06.185
You can't make it so.

00:51:09.750 --> 00:51:11.690
Yeah.

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:14.084
Do you want to--

00:51:23.289 --> 00:51:27.726
AUDIENCE: You use
the same-- is it on?

00:51:27.726 --> 00:51:29.698
MALE SPEAKER: We'll just
repeat the question.

00:51:29.698 --> 00:51:31.177
AUDIENCE: You used
the same phrases

00:51:31.177 --> 00:51:34.135
as you progressed through
the different categories

00:51:34.135 --> 00:51:36.083
of [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:36.083 --> 00:51:37.832
Is that a suggestive
practice or would you

00:51:37.832 --> 00:51:40.051
alter those for a
particular [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:43.010 --> 00:51:45.280
SHARON SALZBERG:
So the comment was

00:51:45.280 --> 00:51:47.530
that I had used the
same phrases as we moved

00:51:47.530 --> 00:51:49.510
through different
categories, and so is

00:51:49.510 --> 00:51:51.600
that the suggestion,
or would you alter them

00:51:51.600 --> 00:51:55.710
as different beings
come to mind?

00:51:55.710 --> 00:52:00.820
Well, here's a balance point,
which is very interesting,

00:52:00.820 --> 00:52:01.780
I think.

00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:03.580
In any meditation,
there's a balance

00:52:03.580 --> 00:52:06.906
that's talked about between
tranquility and calm

00:52:06.906 --> 00:52:09.830
and concentration
on the one side,

00:52:09.830 --> 00:52:11.910
and alertness and
energy and kind

00:52:11.910 --> 00:52:15.059
of aliveness on the other side.

00:52:15.059 --> 00:52:16.850
And we're always working
with that balance,

00:52:16.850 --> 00:52:18.190
because we want both.

00:52:18.190 --> 00:52:20.440
We want to be more
tranquil and calm,

00:52:20.440 --> 00:52:25.120
but not so tranquil and
calm that we're in a stupor.

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:27.600
And we want to be alert and
interested and connected

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:29.450
and learning and
investigating, but not

00:52:29.450 --> 00:52:32.300
so much so that we get
agitated and restless.

00:52:32.300 --> 00:52:35.970
So in every technique
and every method,

00:52:35.970 --> 00:52:37.670
we work around that balance.

00:52:37.670 --> 00:52:40.920
And especially sometimes in
loving kindness practice,

00:52:40.920 --> 00:52:44.440
because it's so active, and
because these are real beings,

00:52:44.440 --> 00:52:47.910
and relationships
are complicated,

00:52:47.910 --> 00:52:50.980
I tend to encourage
a lot of work

00:52:50.980 --> 00:52:55.830
on the kind of tranquility,
calm, concentration side,

00:52:55.830 --> 00:52:58.600
because there's almost nothing
easier in that practice than

00:52:58.600 --> 00:53:02.112
to go off with a lot
of energy and a story.

00:53:02.112 --> 00:53:04.660
Like, well, I thought
you were my benefactor,

00:53:04.660 --> 00:53:07.940
and it worked for a while, but
then I remembered that one time

00:53:07.940 --> 00:53:10.190
when I called you and you
weren't really there for me.

00:53:10.190 --> 00:53:11.630
So maybe you're
not my benefactor.

00:53:11.630 --> 00:53:13.592
Maybe you're my difficult
person, you know?

00:53:13.592 --> 00:53:15.050
Maybe you're in
the wrong category.

00:53:15.050 --> 00:53:16.258
I don't have any benefactors.

00:53:16.258 --> 00:53:17.800
Oh no, I'm so forlorn.

00:53:17.800 --> 00:53:20.190
You know?

00:53:20.190 --> 00:53:23.800
It's very easy, because
relationships are complicated.

00:53:23.800 --> 00:53:25.580
We're complicated.

00:53:25.580 --> 00:53:30.030
And so we're bringing that
right into the meditative arena.

00:53:30.030 --> 00:53:34.620
And so it's not to the
exclusion of having

00:53:34.620 --> 00:53:39.220
that aliveness
and kind of spark.

00:53:39.220 --> 00:53:39.970
It could never be.

00:53:39.970 --> 00:53:43.470
But I just think it's good
to have a sense of structure

00:53:43.470 --> 00:53:46.090
and simplicity that we
can keep returning to.

00:53:46.090 --> 00:53:49.429
And so that would argue
for the same phrases,

00:53:49.429 --> 00:53:50.970
so you're not sitting
there thinking,

00:53:50.970 --> 00:53:52.160
what was my phrasing again?

00:53:54.900 --> 00:53:57.484
And yet, sometimes, someone
will come to mind and almost

00:53:57.484 --> 00:53:58.900
bring their own
phrases with them.

00:53:58.900 --> 00:54:00.580
So you just switch.

00:54:00.580 --> 00:54:05.912
It's not going to be one
of those agitated sessions.

00:54:05.912 --> 00:54:06.412
Yeah.

